"""
mkt-christ: Psalms 22-27
Chapters: 22-27 (Ps 22:1 already present; writing 94 missing verses)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-psalms-22-27.py

Key Christ-connection decisions:
- Ps 22: direct — most NT-cited passion psalm; v7 (Matt 27:39), v8 (Matt 27:43),
  v16 (pierced hands/feet), v18 (John 19:24 explicit quote), v22 (Heb 2:12 explicit quote)
- Ps 23: type — the Good Shepherd (John 10:11,14); cup/table = Eucharist;
  still waters = living water (John 4); eternal dwelling (John 14:2-3)
- Ps 24: direct — King of glory entry (vv7-10) = ascension (Heb 9:11-12; Eph 4:8-10)
- Ps 25: theme — pardon for the name's sake (Acts 4:12); way/truth/life (John 14:6);
  friendship with God (John 15:15)
- Ps 26: shadow — vindication through resurrection (Rom 1:4); temple = Christ's body
  (John 2:19-21); false witnesses at trial (Matt 26:59-60)
- Ps 27: revelation of God — light/salvation/stronghold all claimed by Jesus;
  seeking the face now possible (2 Cor 4:6); wait with courage = Advent posture
"""
import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    # INTENT: merge without overwriting any verse already present in existing
    # CHANGE? Do not alter the guard; concurrent agents depend on append-only behavior
    # VERIFY: run twice; second run should report identical byte count for psalms.json
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NEW_DATA = {"22": {"2": "<p>A direct connection: 'O my God, I cry by day, but you do not answer, and by night, but I find no rest.' The sustained divine silence that follows the cry of dereliction (v1, already present) is what Jesus experienced for the full duration of the crucifixion — from the sixth hour to the ninth (Matt 27:45-46). The 'by day' and 'by night' suggest a duration that exceeds a moment: the forsakenness was not instantaneous but prolonged. The one who had never known divine silence (John 11:41-42: 'Father, I thank you that you have heard me') entered it fully at Golgotha.</p>", "3": "<p>A revelation of God: 'yet you are holy, enthroned on the praises of Israel.' The suffering psalmist affirms the divine holiness even in the midst of forsakenness. The theological precision here is profound: it is precisely because YHWH is holy that the forsakenness occurs. 'He made him to be sin who knew no sin' (2 Cor 5:21) — the holy God cannot face sin without judgment; Christ bearing the world's sin faced the full force of that holiness. The holiness that caused the forsakenness is the same holiness that vindicates the resurrection.</p>", "4": "<p>A revelation of God: 'in you our fathers trusted; they trusted, and you delivered them.' The contrast that makes the psalm's suffering so acute: ancestors who trusted were delivered; the Son who trusts is not (yet) delivered. The patriarchs and Israel through the wilderness — all trusted and were saved. Jesus on the cross is the one for whom the pattern is temporarily reversed, precisely to secure the deliverance of all who come after. The deliverances of the fathers were types and pledges of the one deliverance that requires the non-deliverance of the Son.</p>", "5": "<p>A revelation of God: 'to you they cried and were saved; in you they trusted and were not put to shame.' The covenantal expectation: crying → salvation; trusting → not put to shame. Jesus fulfills the negative of this pattern temporarily at the cross (the trusting one is shamed publicly) in order to fulfill it absolutely in the resurrection. The shame of the cross becomes the ground for 'whoever believes in him will not be put to shame' (Rom 9:33; 10:11, quoting Isa 28:16).</p>", "6": "<p>A direct connection: 'but I am a worm and not a man, scorned by mankind and despised by the people.' The self-description of ultimate humiliation — 'a worm' (<i>tolaat</i>) — anticipates Phil 2:7-8: Christ 'emptied himself, taking the form of a servant... humbled himself by becoming obedient to the point of death, even death on a cross.' The scorned and despised one of Ps 22:6 is identified in Isa 53:3 ('despised and rejected by men') as the Suffering Servant — and in the NT as Jesus crucified (Mark 15:31-32: the chief priests and scribes 'mocked him').</p>", "7": "<p>A direct connection: 'all who see me mock me; they make mouths at me; they wag their heads.' Matt 27:39 cites this verse as fulfilled at the crucifixion: 'those who passed by derided him, wagging their heads and saying...' The physical gesture of head-wagging is not coincidental — the Gospel narrator recognizes it as the fulfillment of the specific gesture Ps 22:7 describes. The entire crucifixion scene in Matthew is narrated through the lens of Ps 22.</p>", "8": "<p>A direct connection: 'He trusts in the LORD; let him deliver him; let him rescue him, for he delights in him!' Matt 27:43 quotes this verse verbatim: 'He trusts in God; let God deliver him now, if he desires him. For he said, I am the Son of God.' The mockers at the cross unwittingly speak the script of Ps 22:8, enacting the prophecy while intending only to taunt. The citation proves the fulfillment is not coincidental — the psalm was composed for this moment.</p>", "9": "<p>A direct connection: 'yet you are he who took me from the womb; you made me trust you at my mother's breasts.' The birth-trust established by YHWH from the beginning. Applied to Christ: the incarnation itself is the divine act of 'taking from the womb' — Luke 2:7, 11-12: 'she gave birth to her firstborn son... today in the city of David a Savior has been born to you, who is Christ the Lord.' The infant Jesus is the one YHWH brought from the womb for the specific mission of Ps 22.</p>", "10": "<p>A direct connection: 'on you was I cast from my birth, and from my mother's womb you have been my God.' The divine claim on Christ from his very entrance into human life. Luke 1:35: 'the Holy Spirit will come upon you, and the power of the Most High will overshadow you; therefore the child to be born will be called holy — the Son of God.' The total God-belonging of Ps 22:10 is expressed in the annunciation: the one born is God's Son, cast upon God from the womb by divine design.</p>", "11": "<p>A shadow: 'be not far from me, for trouble is near, and there is none to help.' The petition for divine nearness in the moment of absolute isolation. At Gethsemane: 'Could you not watch with me one hour?' (Matt 26:40) — the disciples failed to stay near. At the cross: 'they all left him and fled' (Matt 26:56). The aloneness of Ps 22:11 — no human help — was the condition of the crucifixion. The 'none to help' is precisely the situation that required Christ to be the only helper: he who had no human help becomes the helper of all.</p>", "12": "<p>A shadow: 'many bulls encompass me; strong bulls of Bashan surround me.' Bashan — the fertile highland region whose bulls were the largest and most powerful in the ancient world (Amos 4:1: 'cows of Bashan'). The powerful enemies surrounding the psalmist become, in Christ's passion, the combined forces of religious, political, and spiritual opposition — the Sanhedrin, the Roman soldiers, and the demonic powers all converging on Golgotha.</p>", "13": "<p>A shadow: 'they open wide their mouths at me, like a ravening and roaring lion.' The lion metaphor for the enemies who seek to devour — Peter uses this image for the devil himself (1 Pet 5:8: 'your adversary the devil prowls around like a roaring lion, seeking someone to devour'). At the cross, the 'roaring lion' was unleashed against the Son of God. The resurrection is Christ's defeat of the lion: Heb 2:14 ('through death he might destroy the one who has the power of death, that is, the devil').</p>", "14": "<p>A direct connection: 'I am poured out like water, and all my bones are out of joint; my heart is like wax; it is melted within my breast.' The physical description of crucifixion: dehydration ('poured out like water'), joint dislocation from the position on the cross, and cardiac trauma ('heart like wax, melted'). Modern medical analysis of crucifixion confirms the cardiac rupture that John 19:34 may describe: 'one of the soldiers pierced his side with a spear, and at once there came out blood and water' — the water from the pericardial sac consistent with cardiac rupture from the Ps 22:14 description.</p>", "15": "<p>A direct connection: 'my strength is dried up like a potsherd; and my tongue sticks to my jaws; and you lay me in the dust of death.' The extreme thirst ('my tongue sticks to my jaws') directly anticipates John 19:28: 'After this, Jesus, knowing that all was now finished, said (to fulfill the Scripture), I thirst.' The word 'to fulfill the Scripture' in John 19:28 most likely refers to Ps 22:15 (or Ps 69:21: 'for my thirst they gave me sour wine to drink'). The 'dust of death' is the grave into which YHWH 'lays' him — the burial that precedes the resurrection.</p>", "16": "<p>A direct connection: 'for dogs encompass me; a company of evildoers encircles me; they have pierced my hands and my feet.' 'Pierced my hands and my feet' — the crucifixion's specific physical detail, written a millennium before crucifixion was invented as a form of execution. John 20:25,27: Thomas demands to see 'the mark of the nails' in Jesus's hands. John 19:37 quotes Zech 12:10 ('they will look on him whom they have pierced') but the primary fulfillment of 'pierced hands and feet' is Ps 22:16. The early church read Ps 22:16 as predictive specifically of the nailing to the cross.</p>", "17": "<p>A direct connection: 'I can count all my bones — they stare and gloat over me.' 'I can count all my bones' — the emaciation or exposure of the body on the cross, where every rib and joint is visible. The 'staring and gloating' of the crowd at the crucifixion: 'the people stood by, watching' (Luke 23:35) while the rulers scoffed. The public spectacle of the cross — designed by Rome for maximum humiliation and visibility — fulfills the 'stare and gloat' of Ps 22:17.</p>", "18": "<p>A direct connection: 'they divide my garments among them, and for my clothing they cast lots.' John 19:23-24 cites this verse explicitly as fulfilled: 'the soldiers divided his garments among the four of them. They also took his tunic, but it was seamless, woven in one piece from top to bottom, so they said to one another, Let us not tear it, but cast lots for it to see whose it shall be. This was to fulfill the Scripture which says, They divided my garments among them, and for my clothing they cast lots.' One of the most precisely documented fulfillments in all the Gospels.</p>", "19": "<p>A shadow: 'but you, O LORD, do not be far off! O you my help, come quickly to my aid!' The renewed petition from the depths — the turn from lament to petition. The resurrection is the answer to this cry: YHWH did not stay 'far off' permanently. The speed of the divine response ('come quickly') was three days — not instantaneous, but not forever. The confidence beneath the petition is that YHWH will act; the psalm does not end in forsakenness.</p>", "20": "<p>A shadow: 'deliver my soul from the sword, my precious life from the power of the dog!' The 'sword' and the 'dog' — the instruments of violent death. Christ's soul was delivered from the sword through the resurrection: the 'power of death' (Heb 2:14) over which the devil presided was broken when God raised him. The 'precious life' (<i>yechidati</i>, my only one) corresponds to the 'only-begotten Son' (<i>monogenes</i>, John 3:16) — the uniquely precious one whose life was laid down and restored.</p>", "21": "<p>A shadow: 'save me from the mouth of the lion! You have rescued me from the horns of the wild oxen!' The answer to the petition arrives — 'you have rescued me' shifts the psalm to confident retrospect. This is the pivot of Ps 22: from the depths of forsakenness to the assurance of rescue. Applied to Christ: the resurrection is the moment of 'you have rescued me.' The lion's mouth and the wild oxen's horns (the forces of death and evil unleashed at the cross) are defeated by the divine rescue of the third day.</p>", "22": "<p>A direct connection: 'I will tell of your name to my brothers; in the midst of the congregation I will praise you.' Heb 2:12 quotes this verse explicitly as words spoken by the risen Christ: 'he is not ashamed to call them brothers, saying, I will tell of your name to my brothers; in the midst of the congregation I will sing your praise.' The post-resurrection community is the congregation where the risen Christ praises the Father through his people. The 'congregation' of Ps 22:22 becomes the church — those who hear the name proclaimed by the risen one.</p>", "23": "<p>A theme: 'you who fear the LORD, praise him! All you offspring of Jacob, glorify him, and stand in awe of him, all you offspring of Israel!' The summons to the covenant community following the rescue — the resurrection community called to praise. The 'offspring of Jacob' and 'offspring of Israel' who praise the rescued one become, in the NT's universal reading, all who belong to the true Israel — those grafted in through faith in Christ (Rom 11:17-24; Gal 3:29: 'if you are Christ's, then you are Abraham's offspring').</p>", "24": "<p>A revelation of God: 'for he has not despised or scorned the suffering of the afflicted one; he has not hidden his face from him but has listened to his cry for help.' The theological climax of Ps 22: YHWH did not ultimately despise the suffering or hide his face permanently. The resurrection is the proof that the 'hiding of the face' at Golgotha was temporary — the Father heard the cry, and the answer was the empty tomb. The one who cried 'why have you forsaken me?' was heard, and the resurrection was the answer.</p>", "25": "<p>A theme: 'from you comes my praise in the great assembly; my vows I will perform before those who fear him.' The thanksgiving vow performed in the assembly — the <i>todah</i> (thanksgiving sacrifice) following deliverance. Christ's resurrection appearances in the midst of his disciples are the beginning of the 'great assembly' praise. The Eucharist (the Christian <i>todah</i>) is the ongoing performance of the vow: 'do this in remembrance of me' (Luke 22:19) — the risen one's thanksgiving meal continued in his body.</p>", "26": "<p>A theme: 'the afflicted shall eat and be satisfied; those who seek him shall praise the LORD! May your hearts live forever!' 'The afflicted shall eat and be satisfied' — the covenant meal after the affliction: anticipating the resurrection appearances where Jesus ate with his disciples (Luke 24:30-31,41-43; John 21:9-13). The eschatological banquet that the afflicted share after the rescue of Ps 22 is the gospel feast, and ultimately the Marriage Supper of the Lamb (Rev 19:9).</p>", "27": "<p>A theme: 'all the ends of the earth shall remember and turn to the LORD, and all the families of the nations shall worship before you.' The universal missionary vision arising from the individual's rescue: the nations turning to YHWH because of what happened to the anointed sufferer. Paul's entire missionary theology is grounded here: the crucified and risen Christ is the reason 'all the families of the nations' have reason to worship. The Great Commission (Matt 28:18-20) is the activation of this vision.</p>", "28": "<p>A revelation of God: 'for kingship belongs to the LORD, and he rules over the nations.' The universal kingship of YHWH — declared as the ground of the nations' turning (v27). In the NT, this kingship is exercised through the risen Christ: 'all authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me' (Matt 28:18). The nations turn to YHWH (v27) because YHWH rules through his Son — the kingship of Ps 22:28 is the inheritance of Ps 2:8.</p>", "29": "<p>A theme: 'all the prosperous of the earth eat and worship; before him shall bow all who go down to the dust, even the one who could not keep himself alive.' 'All who go down to the dust' — the dead worship YHWH. This is among the earliest OT hints of resurrection worship: even those who have died bow before YHWH. Phil 2:10-11 ('at the name of Jesus every knee should bow, in heaven and on earth and under the earth') makes this universal: the dead as well as the living bow before the risen Christ.</p>", "30": "<p>A theme: 'posterity shall serve him; it shall be told of the Lord to the coming generation.' The intergenerational transmission of the rescue-story — 'it shall be told.' The church's proclamation of the gospel (evangelism) is precisely this: telling the coming generation what YHWH did for his anointed one. The Great Commission establishes the mechanism: 'teaching them to observe all that I have commanded you' (Matt 28:20). The story of Ps 22 is the story that 'shall be told' to every generation.</p>", "31": "<p>A direct connection: 'they shall come and proclaim his righteousness to a people yet to be born, that he has done it.' 'That he has done it' — <i>ki asah</i> — corresponds to the great 'It is finished' (<i>tetelestai</i>, John 19:30): the Greek perfect tense of completed-with-ongoing-results. The proclamation of Ps 22:31 ('he has done it!') is the gospel: the work of rescue is complete. The people 'yet to be born' who will hear this proclamation are the Gentile nations — those who come to faith in every generation since the first Easter.</p>"}, "23": {"1": "<p>A type: 'the LORD is my shepherd; I shall not want.' Jesus explicitly claims this title: 'I am the good shepherd' (John 10:11,14). The type is direct: YHWH the shepherd of Ps 23 is the role Jesus claims as his own, making the identification between YHWH and Jesus explicit in John 10. The 'I shall not want' — the complete sufficiency of the shepherd's provision — is realized in the abundance Christ gives: 'I came that they may have life and have it abundantly' (John 10:10).</p>", "2": "<p>A type: 'he makes me lie down in green pastures. He leads me beside still waters.' The shepherd's provision — rest and water. Christ's provision of rest: 'Come to me, all who labor and are heavy laden, and I will give you rest' (Matt 11:28). The 'living water' of John 4:10-14: 'whoever drinks of the water that I will give him will never be thirsty again.' The still waters of Ps 23 become the rivers of living water that Jesus promises (John 7:38).</p>", "3": "<p>A type: 'he restores my soul. He leads me in paths of righteousness for his name's sake.' 'Restores my soul' — the healing of the whole person, not just external circumstances. Christ's restorative work: the prodigal son's return ('he came to himself,' Luke 15:17), the healing of the paralyzed man (soul and body: 'your sins are forgiven... rise,' Mark 2:5-11). 'Paths of righteousness for his name's sake' — the shepherd leads in covenant integrity for the sake of his own reputation; Christ is himself the path: 'I am the way, and the truth, and the life' (John 14:6).</p>", "4": "<p>A type: 'even though I walk through the valley of the shadow of death, I will fear no evil, for you are with me; your rod and your staff, they comfort me.' Christ is both the one who walks through death's valley and the shepherd who accompanies others through it. The incarnation and crucifixion are YHWH's own shepherd-walk through the valley of death — 'though he die, yet shall he live' (John 11:25). Heb 2:14-15: Jesus shared flesh and blood so 'that through death he might destroy the one who has the power of death... and deliver all those who through fear of death were subject to lifelong slavery.'</p>", "5": "<p>A type: 'you prepare a table before me in the presence of my enemies. You anoint my head with oil; my cup overflows.' The prepared table anticipates the Eucharist: the covenant meal set by the host for the guest, the anointing of the honored guest, the overflowing cup. The Last Supper is set explicitly in the presence of enemies — Judas is at the table, and the cross is hours away. The 'cup that overflows' becomes the cup of blessing (1 Cor 10:16). Christ is both the host who prepares the table and the lamb who is the feast.</p>", "6": "<p>A type: 'surely goodness and mercy shall follow me all the days of my life, and I shall dwell in the house of the LORD forever.' 'Goodness and mercy' (<i>tov vachesed</i>) — the two covenant qualities that 'follow' (pursue, escort) the sheep. In Christ, these qualities are embodied: 'full of grace and truth' (John 1:14). 'The house of the LORD forever' (<i>le'orekh yamim</i>) — the eternal dwelling anticipated by John 14:2-3: 'In my Father's house are many rooms... I go to prepare a place for you... that where I am you may be also.' Ps 23 ends where the gospel ends: eternal habitation with YHWH.</p>"}, "24": {"1": "<p>A revelation of God: 'the earth is the LORD's and the fullness thereof, the world and those who dwell in it.' The comprehensive divine ownership of creation — what Heb 1:2 applies to the Son: 'through whom also he created the world' and who is 'heir of all things.' The earth that belongs to YHWH belongs to Christ as the heir: 'Ask of me, and I will make the nations your heritage, and the ends of the earth your possession' (Ps 2:8). The creator-owner of Ps 24:1 is the one who became flesh and entered his own creation (John 1:10-11).</p>", "2": "<p>A revelation of God: 'for he has founded it upon the seas and established it upon the rivers.' The creator's founding of the ordered world over the cosmic waters — the act of creation that precedes the entrance of the King (vv7-10). Christ as the agent of creation (Col 1:16: 'by him all things were created, in heaven and on earth') grounds the claim that the King of glory entering the gates is the creator returning to his own domain.</p>", "3": "<p>A theme: 'who shall ascend the hill of the LORD? And who shall stand in his holy place?' The question of qualification for approaching YHWH — what the law demands and humanity cannot supply. The answer in v4 (clean hands, pure heart) is the standard that condemns all (Rom 3:23: 'all have sinned and fall short of the glory of God'). Christ is the one who ascends the hill with perfectly clean hands and a pure heart — and the one who, by ascending, opens the access for those who come through him (Heb 10:19-22).</p>", "4": "<p>A theme: 'he who has clean hands and a pure heart, who does not lift up his soul to what is false and does not swear deceitfully.' The fourfold qualification: clean hands (right actions), pure heart (right motives), truthful soul (right orientation), honest oath (right speech). Jesus fulfills all four absolutely. Those who come through him receive this righteousness as imputed: 'he is the source of your life in Christ Jesus, whom God made our wisdom and our righteousness and sanctification and redemption' (1 Cor 1:30).</p>", "5": "<p>A theme: 'he will receive blessing from the LORD and righteousness from the God of his salvation.' 'Righteousness from the God of his salvation' — the gift-righteousness that comes from YHWH himself, not from human performance. This is the gospel: 'the righteousness of God through faith in Jesus Christ for all who believe' (Rom 3:22). The one who ascends (v3) and is qualified (v4) receives this righteousness as gift — and distributes it to all who come through him.</p>", "6": "<p>A theme: 'such is the generation of those who seek him, who seek the face of the God of Jacob.' The community of seekers — those who seek YHWH's face. The face of YHWH that the worshiper seeks is now available: '2 Cor 4:6: God has shone in our hearts to give the light of the knowledge of the glory of God in the face of Jesus Christ.' The generation that seeks the face finds it — in the incarnate Son.</p>", "7": "<p>A direct connection: 'lift up your heads, O gates! And be lifted up, O ancient doors, that the King of glory may come in.' The entry of the King of glory — interpreted in the early church as the ascension of Christ into the heavenly sanctuary. Ps 24:7-10 was read as the heavenly gates being commanded to open for the ascending Christ, who enters not an earthly temple but the true heavenly sanctuary (Heb 9:11-12: 'he entered once for all into the holy places, not by means of the blood of goats and calves but by means of his own blood'). The ancient doors of heaven open for the King who has conquered death.</p>", "8": "<p>A direct connection: 'who is this King of glory? The LORD, strong and mighty, the LORD, mighty in battle!' The identification of the King of glory as YHWH who is 'mighty in battle' (<i>gibbor milchamah</i>) — the divine warrior. Applied to Christ's resurrection and ascension: the 'battle' won is the battle against sin, death, and the devil (Col 2:15: 'he disarmed the rulers and authorities and put them to open shame, by triumphing over them in him'). The King of glory who ascends through the heavenly gates is the risen Christ who has won the cosmic battle.</p>", "9": "<p>A direct connection: 'lift up your heads, O gates! And lift them up, O ancient doors, that the King of glory may come in.' The doubled summons — the gates asked twice to open — emphasizes the significance of the entry. The ancient church's Easter and Ascension liturgy used Ps 24:7-10 dramatically: a deacon would cry out 'lift up your heads!' and the congregation would respond with 'who is the King of glory?' re-enacting the heavenly procession. The liturgical use captures the psalm's Christological meaning.</p>", "10": "<p>A direct connection: 'who is this King of glory? The LORD of hosts, he is the King of glory!' The final identification: YHWH of hosts as the King of glory who enters the gates. The NT identifies this King as Jesus: 'he who descended is the one who also ascended far above all the heavens, that he might fill all things' (Eph 4:10). The 'LORD of hosts' who commands the heavenly armies is the Christ who 'leads a host of captives' (Eph 4:8, quoting Ps 68:18) in his ascension — taking with him those who had been captive to sin and death.</p>"}, "25": {"1": "<p>A theme: 'to you, O LORD, I lift my soul.' The total surrender of the self — soul offered upward to YHWH. Christ's Gethsemane prayer is this posture in its purest form: 'Father, if you are willing, remove this cup from me. Nevertheless, not my will, but yours, be done' (Luke 22:42). The soul lifted to YHWH even when what YHWH wills is the cross — this is the acrostic psalm's opening posture fulfilled in the Son's absolute obedience.</p>", "2": "<p>A theme: 'O my God, in you I trust; let me not be put to shame; let not my enemies exult over me.' Trust and the petition against shame. The resurrection is the answer: the one who trusted was not ultimately put to shame. Rom 10:11 (quoting Isa 28:16): 'no one who believes in him will be put to shame.' The anti-shame promise of the gospel flows from the resurrection of the trusting one — he was not put to shame, and those in him share his vindication.</p>", "3": "<p>A revelation of God: 'indeed, none who wait for you shall be put to shame; they shall be ashamed who are wantonly treacherous.' The universal promise to the waiting ones — 'none who wait for you.' The waiting community (Advent) is those who trust the Father's timing, as Jesus trusted the Father's timing through three days in the tomb. The resurrection demonstrates that waiting on YHWH is not futile: the treacherous who exulted at the cross were put to shame on Easter morning.</p>", "4": "<p>A theme: 'make me to know your ways, O LORD; teach me your paths.' The prayer for divine guidance — the disciple's request. Jesus is himself 'the way, and the truth, and the life' (John 14:6) — the answer to the prayer of Ps 25:4 is not an abstract map but a person. The divine path and the divine teacher become one in the incarnation: Christ does not merely show the way, he is the way.</p>", "5": "<p>A theme: 'lead me in your truth and teach me, for you are the God of my salvation; for you I wait all the day long.' 'The God of my salvation' — the identification of YHWH as Savior. The Hebrew root <i>yasha</i> (salvation) is the root of the name Jesus (Yeshua). Ps 25:5 prays to 'the God of my salvation' — the NT announces that this God has given salvation a face and a name: Jesus, the God-with-us.</p>", "6": "<p>A revelation of God: 'remember your mercy, O LORD, and your steadfast love, for they have been from of old.' The appeal to divine memory — YHWH's <i>chesed</i> and mercy as the 'from of old' covenant constants. The incarnation is the most radical expression of this eternal mercy: 'the grace of God has appeared' (Titus 2:11) — what was 'from of old' in divine character became visible and tangible in Jesus. 'From of old' mercy became, in the fullness of time, the mercy that died and rose.</p>", "7": "<p>A revelation of God: 'remember not the sins of my youth or my transgressions; according to your steadfast love remember me, for the sake of your goodness, O LORD!' The petition for the non-remembrance of sin — what the new covenant explicitly promises: 'I will remember their sin no more' (Jer 31:34; Heb 10:17). Christ's atoning work is the basis of this non-remembrance: sins covered by his blood are 'remembered no more' (Heb 8:12). Ps 25:7 petitions what the new covenant delivers.</p>", "8": "<p>A revelation of God: 'good and upright is the LORD; therefore he instructs sinners in the way.' The divine goodness and uprightness as the reason for teaching sinners. Christ as the divine teacher: 'he opened his mouth and taught them' (Matt 5:2) — the Sermon on the Mount is the 'good and upright LORD' instructing sinners in the way. The teacher is not a detached pedagogue but the incarnate God who himself is the curriculum.</p>", "9": "<p>A theme: 'he leads the humble in what is right and teaches the humble his way.' The humble (<i>anavim</i>) as the recipients of divine instruction. 'Blessed are the meek, for they shall inherit the earth' (Matt 5:5, quoting Ps 37:11). Christ himself is 'meek and lowly in heart' (Matt 11:29) — the teacher of the humble is himself the exemplar of humility. He both teaches the humble way and embodies it.</p>", "10": "<p>A revelation of God: 'all the paths of the LORD are steadfast love and faithfulness, for those who keep his covenant and his testimonies.' Every divine path is characterized by <i>chesed</i> and <i>emet</i> — the two covenant qualities that Ps 85:10 personifies meeting. In Christ, these qualities are fully embodied: 'full of grace and truth' (John 1:14). The paths of YHWH that are <i>chesed</i>-and-<i>emet</i> lead through the incarnation, the cross, and the resurrection.</p>", "11": "<p>A direct connection: 'for your name's sake, O LORD, pardon my guilt, for it is great.' The ground of pardon: the divine name, not human merit. Acts 4:12: 'there is no other name under heaven given among men by which we must be saved.' The name of YHWH by which Ps 25:11 seeks pardon becomes, in the NT, the name of Jesus — 'everyone who calls on the name of the Lord shall be saved' (Acts 2:21; Rom 10:13). The prayer for pardon for the name's sake is answered in the name of Jesus.</p>", "12": "<p>A theme: 'who is the man who fears the LORD? Him will he instruct in the way that he should choose.' The fear of the LORD again (Ps 111:10: the beginning of wisdom) as the prerequisite for divine instruction. The instruction the God-fearer receives is ultimately Christ himself — the one who is 'the way' (John 14:6). The 'way to choose' is the choice to follow Christ.</p>", "13": "<p>A theme: 'his soul shall abide in well-being, and his offspring shall inherit the land.' The covenant promise of land-inheritance for the offspring of the one who fears YHWH. Christ is both the heir who inherits (Ps 2:8; Heb 1:2) and the one through whom his 'offspring' (those adopted as children through him: Gal 3:29; 4:7) inherit the ultimate land — the new creation (Rev 21:1-4; Matt 5:5: 'the meek shall inherit the earth').</p>", "14": "<p>A revelation of God: 'the friendship of the LORD is for those who fear him, and he makes known to them his covenant.' 'The friendship of the LORD' (<i>sod YHWH</i>, the intimate council/secret of YHWH) — the closest possible covenant relationship. Jesus elevates this beyond servanthood: 'no longer do I call you servants... but I have called you friends, for all that I have heard from my Father I have made known to you' (John 15:15). The covenant secret of Ps 25:14 becomes the full disclosure of the Father in Christ.</p>", "15": "<p>A theme: 'my eyes are ever toward the LORD, for he will pluck my feet out of the net.' The constant orientation toward YHWH — the undivided attention that resists the nets of temptation. Jesus's eyes were 'ever toward' the Father throughout his ministry: 'the Son can do nothing of his own accord, but only what he sees the Father doing' (John 5:19). The feet-from-the-net rescue is what Christ accomplishes for those who are trapped: 'if the Son sets you free, you will be free indeed' (John 8:36).</p>", "16": "<p>A shadow: 'turn to me and be gracious to me, for I am lonely and afflicted.' The loneliness and affliction of the covenant petitioner. Christ entered maximum loneliness: abandoned by his disciples (Mark 14:50), denied by Peter (Mark 14:66-72), forsaken by the Father in the sense of Ps 22:1. The one who enters that loneliness to its depth becomes the one who promises 'I am with you always, to the end of the age' (Matt 28:20) — having inhabited every degree of isolation so that no one who trusts him is ultimately alone.</p>", "17": "<p>A shadow: 'the troubles of my heart are enlarged; bring me out of my distresses.' 'Troubles of my heart are enlarged' — the interior expansion of distress. The Gethsemane prayer is this psalm: 'My soul is very sorrowful, even to death' (Matt 26:38). The enlargement of heart-trouble to the point of death is what Christ entered so that those who come to him find their troubles can be brought to the one who knows their full depth from personal experience.</p>", "18": "<p>A shadow: 'consider my affliction and my trouble, and forgive all my sins.' The petition that affliction and sin be addressed together — the physical and the spiritual. Christ's healing ministry addressed both simultaneously: 'which is easier, to say, Your sins are forgiven, or to say, Rise and walk?' (Matt 9:5). The atonement addresses the root (sin) through which all affliction ultimately flows; the resurrection addresses the consequence (death) that sin produces.</p>", "19": "<p>A shadow: 'consider how many are my enemies, and with what violent hatred they hate me.' The violent hatred of enemies — what Christ experienced at his arrest, trial, and crucifixion. 'They hated me without a cause' (John 15:25, quoting Ps 35:19; 69:4) — the gratuitous hatred of the innocent one. The enemies' violent hatred was the occasion for Christ's non-retaliating love: 'Father, forgive them, for they know not what they do' (Luke 23:34).</p>", "20": "<p>A shadow: 'oh, guard my soul, and deliver me! Let me not be put to shame, for I take refuge in you.' The soul-guarding petition — Christ's absolute trust in the Father's guarding even through death. John 10:17-18: 'I lay down my life that I may take it up again. No one takes it from me, but I lay it down of my own accord.' The soul that takes refuge in YHWH is the soul that YHWH guards through death and raises on the third day.</p>", "21": "<p>A theme: 'may integrity and uprightness preserve me, for I wait for you.' Integrity and uprightness as the petition's basis — and as the posture of waiting. Christ's integrity was absolute; his uprightness (righteousness) was the ground on which the Father vindicated him through resurrection. Those who 'wait for YHWH' (Ps 25:3: 'none who wait for you shall be put to shame') share in the vindication of the upright one who waited through the cross.</p>", "22": "<p>A theme: 'redeem Israel, O God, out of all his troubles.' The closing petition expands from the individual to the nation — the personal lament opens onto the corporate redemption. Christ is both the redeemer of Israel (Luke 24:21: the disciples hoped 'he was the one to redeem Israel' — and he was, though not as they expected) and the redeemer of all who are 'Israel' by faith (Rom 9:6-8; Gal 6:16). The redemption from 'all his troubles' is the comprehensive salvation the gospel promises.</p>"}, "26": {"1": "<p>A shadow: 'vindicate me, O LORD, for I have walked in my integrity, and I have trusted in the LORD without wavering.' The vindication prayer — 'vindicate me' (<i>shophteni</i>, judge me, give me justice). The resurrection is the divine vindication of Jesus: 'declared to be the Son of God in power according to the Spirit of holiness by his resurrection from the dead' (Rom 1:4). The 'walking in integrity without wavering' is fulfilled only in Jesus — whose trust in the Father never wavered even through the cry of dereliction.</p>", "2": "<p>A shadow: 'prove me, O LORD, and try me; test my heart and my mind.' The invitation to divine examination — utterly confident only in the mouth of the sinless one. Jesus was tested supremely in Gethsemane and on the cross; the Father's examination found no wavering. The testing of Ps 26:2 is what Jesus passed perfectly — 'he learned obedience through what he suffered' (Heb 5:8) and emerged from every test without sin (Heb 4:15: 'one who in every respect has been tempted as we are, yet without sin').</p>", "3": "<p>A theme: 'for your steadfast love is before my eyes, and I walk in your faithfulness.' Walking in the light of divine <i>chesed</i> — the <i>chesed</i>-shaped life. Christ's life was the supreme embodiment of walking in divine faithfulness: 'the Son can do nothing of his own accord, but only what he sees the Father doing' (John 5:19). The faithfulness of the Father before Jesus's eyes shaped every step of his ministry, the cross, and the resurrection.</p>", "4": "<p>A theme: 'I do not sit with men of falsehood, nor do I consort with hypocrites.' The moral separation — not associating with the deceitful. Jesus ate with sinners but never participated in their sin; he engaged the hypocrites (Pharisees, scribes) but never adopted their hypocrisy. His sharpest rebukes were for religious hypocrisy (Matt 23). The one who sat with sinners in order to save them never sat among the hypocritical in their hypocrisy.</p>", "5": "<p>A theme: 'I hate the assembly of evildoers, and I will not sit with the wicked.' The hatred of evil as a moral affirmation, not mere avoidance. Jesus's 'cleansing of the temple' (John 2:13-17; Matt 21:12-13) is the active expression of this hatred: turning over the money-changers' tables, driving out those who had turned the house of prayer into a market. 'Zeal for your house will consume me' (John 2:17, quoting Ps 69:9) — the hatred of what desecrates the holy.</p>", "6": "<p>A shadow: 'I wash my hands in innocence and go around your altar, O LORD.' 'I wash my hands in innocence' — the ritual declaration of purity before approaching the altar. The grim irony of the Passion narrative: Pilate 'washed his hands before the crowd, saying, I am innocent of this man's blood' (Matt 27:24) — performing the ritual of Ps 26:6 over the one who actually had clean hands. The innocent one was handed over by the one who washed his hands to claim innocence.</p>", "7": "<p>A theme: 'proclaiming thanksgiving aloud, and telling all your wondrous deeds.' The proclamation of YHWH's wondrous works — the <i>todah</i> testimony. Christ's own proclamation of the Father's works: 'I have manifested your name to the people whom you gave me' (John 17:6). After the resurrection, the proclamation of 'wondrous deeds' becomes the content of apostolic preaching: the miracle of the cross and resurrection as YHWH's supreme <i>niphlaot</i>.</p>", "8": "<p>A revelation of God: 'O LORD, I love the habitation of your house and the place where your glory dwells.' The love of the divine dwelling — the temple as the place of divine presence. Jesus identifies himself as the new temple: 'destroy this temple, and in three days I will raise it up... he was speaking about the temple of his body' (John 2:19-21). The love of the place where glory dwells is the love of Christ himself — in whom 'the whole fullness of deity dwells bodily' (Col 2:9).</p>", "9": "<p>A theme: 'do not sweep my soul away with sinners, nor my life with bloodthirsty men.' The petition for separation from the fate of sinners. Christ was 'numbered with the transgressors' (Isa 53:12; Mark 15:27-28: crucified between two criminals) voluntarily — not swept away with them but willingly placed among them to bear their fate. The distinction of Ps 26:9 was preserved in his innocence even while he bore the punishment of the guilty.</p>", "10": "<p>A theme: 'in whose hands are evil devices, and whose right hands are full of bribes.' The characterization of the wicked — evil hands and bribed right hands. Judas received thirty pieces of silver (Matt 26:15) — the bribe that handed over the innocent. The evil devices and bribes of Ps 26:10 are fulfilled in the betrayal that set the Passion in motion.</p>", "11": "<p>A shadow: 'but as for me, I shall walk in my integrity; redeem me, and be gracious to me.' The integrity-walk as the ground of the redemption-petition. Christ walked in absolute integrity and was redeemed from death by the Father's grace — the resurrection as the divine graciousness extended to the one who walked perfectly. Those who are 'in Christ' walk in his imputed integrity and receive the same redemption (Eph 1:7: 'in him we have redemption through his blood').</p>", "12": "<p>A theme: 'my foot stands on level ground; in the great assembly I will bless the LORD.' The stable standing and public praise — the posture of the vindicated worshiper. Christ's resurrection appearances are his 'standing on level ground' before the community: he stands, eats, shows his wounds, and commissions his disciples. The 'great assembly' where blessing occurs is the church — his ongoing body through whom he continues to bless the Father.</p>"}, "27": {"1": "<p>A revelation of God: 'the LORD is my light and my salvation; whom shall I fear? The LORD is the stronghold of my life; of whom shall I be afraid?' The threefold identification: light, salvation, stronghold. Jesus claims all three: 'I am the light of the world' (John 8:12; 9:5); his name means salvation (Matt 1:21); he is the stronghold for those who take refuge in him (Pss 2:12; 18:2). The fearlessness of Ps 27:1 is the fearlessness Christ both embodies and imparts: 'Do not be afraid' is his consistent word (Matt 14:27; 28:10; Rev 1:17).</p>", "2": "<p>A shadow: 'when evildoers assail me to eat up my flesh, my adversaries and foes, it is they who stumble and fall.' The adversaries who 'eat up flesh' — the violent opposition that falls on itself. At the arrest in Gethsemane, those who came to take Jesus 'drew back and fell to the ground' (John 18:6) when Jesus identified himself — a momentary preview of Ps 27:2's promise. The ultimate falling of the adversaries is the defeat of all opposition in the resurrection.</p>", "3": "<p>A shadow: 'though an army encamp against me, my heart shall not fear; though war arise against me, yet I will be confident.' The fearlessness before military opposition — the confidence that is not bravado but trust. Jesus in Gethsemane when 'a great crowd came... with swords and clubs' (Matt 26:47): no fear, no flight, only the forward-moving trust: 'Rise, let us be going' (Matt 26:46). The confidence of Ps 27:3 is the Gethsemane calm of the one who trusts the Father's path.</p>", "4": "<p>A revelation of God: 'one thing have I asked of the LORD, that will I seek after: that I may dwell in the house of the LORD all the days of my life, to gaze upon the beauty of the LORD and to inquire in his temple.' The singular focus — to dwell with YHWH and behold his beauty. Christ's prayer in John 17:24: 'Father, I desire that they also... may be with me where I am, to see my glory that you have given me.' The gazing upon the divine beauty that Ps 27:4 seeks is what Christ promises to his own: the beatific vision, the eternal dwelling with YHWH begun now and completed in the resurrection age.</p>", "5": "<p>A revelation of God: 'for he will hide me in his shelter in the day of trouble; he will conceal me under the cover of his tent; he will lift me high upon a rock.' The divine hiding and lifting — the protection of the Father for the Son in the 'day of trouble' (the crucifixion). The Father did not abandon the Son to permanent death but 'lifted him high' in the resurrection and ascension: 'God has highly exalted him' (Phil 2:9). The rock upon which he is set is the resurrection victory.</p>", "6": "<p>A theme: 'and now my head shall be lifted up above my enemies all around me, and I will offer in his tent sacrifices with shouts of joy; I will sing and make melody to the LORD.' 'My head lifted above my enemies' — the resurrection reversal: the head bowed in death is lifted in vindication. The 'sacrifices with shouts of joy' anticipate the Eucharist — the <i>todah</i> meal offered in the tent of the new covenant by the risen Christ through his community.</p>", "7": "<p>A revelation of God: 'hear, O LORD, when I cry aloud; be gracious to me and answer me!' The petition for the divine hearing. Heb 5:7: 'In the days of his flesh, Jesus offered up prayers and supplications, with loud cries and tears, to him who was able to save him from death, and he was heard because of his reverence.' The cry of Ps 27:7 is answered in Christ's resurrection: YHWH heard and answered — and the answer was the empty tomb.</p>", "8": "<p>A revelation of God: 'you have said, Seek my face. My heart says to you, Your face, LORD, I seek.' The divine command and the human response — the dialogue of seeking. The face of YHWH that the whole OT sought to see is now available in Christ: 'No one has ever seen God; the only God, who is at the Father's side, he has made him known' (John 1:18). 'The light of the knowledge of the glory of God in the face of Jesus Christ' (2 Cor 4:6) — the face YHWH said to seek has been found in the incarnation.</p>", "9": "<p>A shadow: 'hide not your face from me. Turn not your servant away in anger, O you who have been my help. Cast me not off; forsake me not, O God of my salvation!' The dread of divine face-hiding — the counterpart of Ps 22:1 ('why have you forsaken me?'). Christ entered the face-hiding at its maximum depth so that it would not be the final word for any who trust him. The 'do not forsake me' of Ps 27:9 is answered by the resurrection-promise: 'I am with you always, to the end of the age' (Matt 28:20).</p>", "10": "<p>A revelation of God: 'for my father and my mother have forsaken me, but the LORD will take me in.' The abandonment of the closest human bonds — and the divine adoption that supersedes them. The cross was the moment of maximum human abandonment: 'they all left him and fled' (Matt 26:56). Yet the Father 'took him in' in the resurrection. For those who are forsaken, Christ promises the same adoption: 'I will not leave you as orphans; I will come to you' (John 14:18).</p>", "11": "<p>A theme: 'teach me your way, O LORD, and lead me on a level path because of my enemies.' 'Teach me your way' — the discipleship prayer. Christ is both the teacher of the way (the Sermon on the Mount, the parables) and the way itself (John 14:6). The 'level path' despite enemies is the path Christ walked to the cross and through it — the level path that is not detoured by opposition but goes straight through it.</p>", "12": "<p>A shadow: 'give me not up to the will of my adversaries; for false witnesses have risen against me, and they breathe out violence.' 'False witnesses have risen against me' — the trial before the Sanhedrin: 'the chief priests and the whole council were seeking false testimony against Jesus that they might put him to death, but they found none, though many false witnesses came forward' (Matt 26:59-60). The false witnesses of Ps 27:12 are the false witnesses at Jesus's trial.</p>", "13": "<p>A revelation of God: 'I believe that I shall look upon the goodness of the LORD in the land of the living!' The confident faith in divine goodness — the resurrection hope before the resurrection happens. 'The land of the living' — the realm of life beyond death: Christ's resurrection establishes that the land of the living is not a metaphor but a destination. 'I am the resurrection and the life' (John 11:25): the land of the living is where Christ dwells, and he invites his own to join him there.</p>", "14": "<p>A revelation of God: 'wait for the LORD; be strong, and let your heart take courage; wait for the LORD!' The closing summons — wait, take courage, wait again. The Advent posture: the community that waits for Christ's return. 'Wait for the LORD' is the posture between Easter and the Parousia — courage sustained by the certainty that the God who raised Jesus will complete what he has begun. The psalm that began with fearlessness (v1: 'whom shall I fear?') ends with courageous waiting — the two poles of the Christian life.</p>"}}

if __name__ == '__main__':
    book = 'psalms'
    source = 'mkt-christ'
    existing = load_comm(source, book)
    merge_comm(existing, NEW_DATA)
    save_comm(source, book, existing)
    for ch, vv in NEW_DATA.items():
        saved = existing.get(ch, {})
        missing = [v for v in vv if v not in saved]
        print(f'  ch {ch}: {len(vv)} entries, {len(missing)} missing after merge')
